{
  "response_text": "Available green biomass initiates at approximately 45,000 units and follows a U-shaped trajectory with superimposed multi-decadal cyclical variations. During the first four years, the system exhibits minor fluctuation, reaching approximately 45,261 units before entering a pronounced decline. This depletion phase intensifies through year 9, marking an inflection point where the rate of loss begins moderating, and continues until year 27 when biomass reaches its minimum value of approximately 42,057 units.\n\nFollowing this nadir, the system enters a recovery phase. Between years 27 and 33, the decline stabilizes into a period of no significant trend. Thereafter, a sustained increasing trajectory commences, accelerating notably between years 44 and 54 where the rate of biomass accumulation reaches its maximum velocity. A second inflection point at year 49 signals a transition to more gradual—but persistent—growth rates. By year 50, the system has crossed a critical threshold into a steady accumulation phase.\n\nFrom year 50 through year 100, biomass increases monotonically across all measurement windows, though at progressively decelerating rates, ultimately reaching approximately 60,535 units. This terminal value represents a substantial increase of roughly 34% above initial conditions and 44% above the minimum recorded at year 27. Throughout the entire series, oscillations with a periodicity of approximately 49 years are evident, particularly during intervals spanning years 10-20 and 41-49.\n\nThese dynamics suggest that initial stocking levels of 90 animals per household exceed sustainable carrying capacity under the variable rainfall regime (mean 200 units, standard deviation 100), driving the early biomass depletion. As farmers employ learning-by-doing and social learning strategies—observing neighbors within the one-patch knowledge radius—they progressively reduce herd sizes to alleviate grazing pressure. Because livestock reproduction is inactive, these reductions permanently decrease animal numbers, allowing vegetation to recover and accumulate biomass beyond initial levels once conservative management strategies diffuse through the population. The sustained accumulation throughout the latter 50 years indicates that adaptive learning successfully facilitates stocking decisions that enable long-term pasture rehabilitation despite stochastic environmental conditions."
}

